ritical paradigms. By engaging the readers with familiar areas of critical discourse (such as postcolonial criticism, 'national cinema', 'genre', 'authorship' and 'stardom') the book aims to introduce within such contexts the 'unfamiliar' case studies which will be explored in depth and detail. The advantage of such an approach is that it works with the dynamics of familiarity/unfamiliarity and resists the temptation to construct Asian cinemas as a gallery of exotic objects that might be particularly fascinating but remain deeply distant and foreign.KeyFeatures:A comprehensive study of Asian cinemas, including Hong Kong, Japan, China, India, Turkey and TaiwanAn accessible guide for the study and research of Asian cinema which addresses undergraduate and postgraduate students and researchersEach section contains a contextualising introductionIncludes key texts by Ackbar Abbas, Rey Chow, David Desser, Dimitris Eleftheriotis, Nezih Erdo  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAbbas, Ackbar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Rey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesser, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEleftheriotis, Dimitris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErdoğan, Nezih, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarwood, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGopalan, Lalitha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGürata, Ahmet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Leon,